Comment_contributor: The number for 13 includes a second form c͗ásti a·tú·m͗i. It should include the initial compound malús·iyáté, which means 'added to 10'; and indeed all the numbers from 10 to 15 have a second form with a·tú·m͗i substituted for aˑýeq̓ti. There are other variants of the compounding of simple numeral names, but this suffices to show that you have a quinary system with separate names for 5, 10, and 20.
